; A bare (throw :tag) in a non-void function needs a sentinel: either the
; function's :on-error metadata or an explicit (throw :tag VALUE). Without either
; the compiler refuses.
(defn int f ((int x))
  (when (< x 0) (throw :neg))
  (return x))
;==EXPECTED-ERROR==
<stdin>:4:1: error[macro]: throw without a value needs the function's :on-error sentinel, or write (throw :tag VALUE)
(defn int f ((int x))
^

Signature: (defn &rest args)
Doc: Define a C function. Optional leading flags :static and/or :inline emit the corresponding C specifiers (e.g. `static inline`). For an inline function in a single translation unit prefer :inline :static so it links at -O0.
Example: (defn :inline :static int sq ((int x)) (return (* x x)))
